<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Pricing strategy fundamentals</span><h2 class="h2">The 4 questions to answer first</h2><ol class="ol"><li><strong>What's your target ARPM (average revenue per member per month)?</strong> Drives everything else.</li><li><strong>What's your member acquisition cost (CAC) and acceptable CAC ceiling?</strong> Generally CAC ≤ 1/3 LTV.</li><li><strong>What pricing tiers does your target market expect?</strong> Local competitive landscape matters.</li><li><strong>How will you handle pricing changes over time?</strong> Grandfather existing members or raise across the board?</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Pricing benchmarks by format</span><h2 class="h2">May 2026 typical price points</h2><div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Format</th><th>Entry tier</th><th>Mid tier</th><th>Premium tier</th><th>Typical ARPM</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Personal training studio</td><td>\$200-\$400/mo</td><td>\$400-\$600/mo</td><td>\$600-\$1,200/mo</td><td>\$300-\$500</td></tr><tr><td>Boutique HIIT / strength</td><td>\$120-\$180/mo</td><td>\$170-\$250/mo</td><td>\$220-\$350/mo</td><td>\$175-\$225</td></tr><tr><td>Boutique cycling / barre / yoga</td><td>\$120-\$180/mo</td><td>\$160-\$220/mo</td><td>\$200-\$300/mo</td><td>\$165-\$210</td></tr><tr><td>Pilates Reformer</td><td>\$200-\$300/mo</td><td>\$280-\$400/mo</td><td>\$400-\$600/mo</td><td>\$280-\$380</td></tr><tr><td>CrossFit affiliate</td><td>\$130-\$200/mo</td><td>\$170-\$240/mo</td><td>\$200-\$280/mo</td><td>\$170-\$220</td></tr><tr><td>Mid-tier full-service</td><td>\$30-\$60/mo</td><td>\$60-\$100/mo</td><td>\$100-\$180/mo</td><td>\$45-\$75</td></tr><tr><td>Premium full-service / luxury</td><td>\$150-\$250/mo</td><td>\$250-\$400/mo</td><td>\$400-\$800/mo</td><td>\$220-\$400</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Membership tier structure</span><h2 class="h2">How most operators build the menu</h2><h3 class="h3">Common 3-tier structure</h3><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Entry tier:</strong> limited (4-8 classes/month, or restricted hours). Anchor pricing low to drive trial.</li><li><strong>Mid tier:</strong> the value sweet spot. 80-100% of members. Anchor price-per-class lowest here.</li><li><strong>Premium tier:</strong> unlimited + perks (guest passes, retail discounts, recovery services). Drives ARPM up; relatively few members but profitable.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Annual vs monthly</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Annual prepay typically discounted 10-15% vs monthly equivalent.</li><li>Annual members retain meaningfully better than monthly (lower commitment-decision friction).</li><li>Most operators offer both; aggressive operators push annual via signup-flow framing.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">Trial / intro offers</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Boutique standard: 7-day intro at \$30-\$50 OR free trial class.</li><li>CrossFit standard: free intro + onboarding sessions.</li><li>Premium PT: free consult + sample session.</li><li>Big-box: free 7-day pass.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">The sales process at a gym</span><h2 class="h2">Tour → trial → close</h2><h3 class="h3">Traditional sales process (legacy)</h3><ol class="ol"><li>Lead inquiry → membership consultant follows up (often slow)</li><li>Tour booked → in-person tour conducted by membership consultant</li><li>Tour ends → consultant pitches membership; close-rate-pressure tactics common</li><li>Member signs OR membership consultant follows up over days/weeks</li></ol><h3 class="h3">AI-augmented sales process (2026)</h3><ol class="ol"><li>Lead inquiry → AI agent responds within 60 seconds via SMS, qualifies conversationally, books tour</li><li>Tour confirmations + reminders + day-of context sent automatically</li><li>Tour conducted by GM, head coach, or membership consultant (human-led)</li><li>Post-tour: AI agent sends personalized next-step content based on what was discussed; flags for human follow-up if signals indicate need</li></ol><p class="body">Operators using AI-augmented sales process typically convert 1.5-2x more leads into members than traditional process — primarily because the agent handles the pre-tour qualification and post-tour follow-through that humans inconsistently execute.</p><p class="body"><a href="https://fitagentic.ai" style="color:#00C853;">fitagentic.ai</a> is the platform purpose-built for this hybrid agent-human sales process.</p></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Pricing changes — when and how</span><h2 class="h2">Operator guide</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Typical cadence:</strong> 3-7% increase annually, particularly at boutique formats where premium pricing supports it.</li><li><strong>Grandfather existing members</strong> at their current price for 6-12 months, then transition. Reduces churn risk.</li><li><strong>Communicate proactively</strong> 60-90 days ahead. Frame around investments made (new equipment, new programming, additional staff).</li><li><strong>Use price increases to test market sensitivity</strong>: if churn doesn't spike, you under-priced previously.</li><li><strong>New members get new pricing immediately</strong>; existing members get notice. Standard pattern.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><span class="lbl">Common pricing mistakes</span><h2 class="h2">Where money is left on the table</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Pricing too low relative to local market.</strong> Trainer-to-owner transitions particularly do this; positioning is premium but pricing is mid.</li><li><strong>Too few tiers.</strong> Single-tier pricing loses both price-sensitive and premium customers.</li><li><strong>No annual prepay option.</strong> Misses out on retention benefit + cash-flow benefit.</li><li><strong>Aggressive cancellation friction.</strong> Net-negative for long-term brand and referral economics, even though it preserves short-term revenue.</li><li><strong>Never raising prices.</strong> ARPM erodes vs inflation; can't recover without ugly increase.</li></ul></div></section>

